number of pedestrian, safety, and other related traffic studies conducted in the area to obtain a
better understanding of the issues that are continuously brought to their attention by local
The City, as well as the homeowners living in the neighborhoods adjacent to the above
referenced corridors, have raised concerns over the traffic flow impacts related to the FDOT’s
recent construction project. These concerns are primarily due to an increase in traffic volume
and cut-through traffic along 13th Avenue in relation to the access/median opening
modifications made in conjunction with the Department’s safety project. The City and
homeowners claim that the cut-through traffic is generated by motorists traveling northbound
along Federal Highway/US 1, southwest of the study limits, who decide to by-pass the relatively
congested Young Circle area by means of the local street network. Area residents continue to
express similar safety related concerns with regard to the lack of safe locations for pedestrian
and bicycle crossings along Hollywood Boulevard to City officials. The concerns are mainly due
to the presence of the raised landscaped median that was installed by the Department during
The City has subsequently expressed an interest in exploring the feasibility of making some
additional geometric design and access modifications along Hollywood Boulevard to address
these concerns. Based on the City’s request, ATEC has performed an evaluation and
operational assessment of three possible design alternatives that include the installation of
roundabouts. The roundabout concepts for the corridor along State Road 820/Hollywood
Boulevard (approximately from 16th Avenue to 9th Avenue) were developed with input from City
The traffic data was used to analyze the intersections along the Hollywood Boulevard/SR 820
corridor under three Alternatives. The three alternatives analyzed show the installation of two
single-lane roundabouts. Roundabouts alleviate the delays experienced on the NB and SB
approaches of the 13th Avenue intersection. In addition, the installation of these roundabouts
would give full access to additional minor street approaches to Hollywood Boulevard/SR 820
without the existing median restrictions, thus improving the traffic operations on adjacent streets
and reducing the traffic collection (cut-through traffic) on 13th Avenue. The installation of
roundabouts would provide a safety factor concerning pedestrians and bicycles as well as an
enhancement of the aesthetics along the corridor. The three different alternatives were analyzed
using Synchro 8 and compared to the roadway’s existing conditions.
Based solely on the micro-simulation model, Alternative 1 is overall preferred to Alternatives 2A
and 2B. Despite being more restrictive in its movements, Alternative 1 allows for less delay
along the major east and westbound through movements. This is mainly related to the removal
of the existing traffic signal at 13th Avenue. The NB/SB approaches can still go around the
roundabouts to switch directions, without having to wait for gaps, but be at yield condition
However, the crash data at the intersection of Hollywood Boulevard and 13th Avenue shows a
real need to improve accessibility at the intersections. Alternatives 2A and 2B improve access
at a marginal expense to the traffic conditions. The intersection delay and LOS are slightly
increased under Alternatives 2A and 2B, mainly due modifying the minor street approaches
from restricted access to full access. Both Alternatives maintain an acceptable LOS and Delay
for all intersections (AM and PM). Alternative 2B sustains a single lane before and after the
roundabouts, which slightly reduces the potential for sideswipes crashes; however, it also
decreases the lane capacity, increases the vehicle delay and LOS, elongates the vehicle
queuing, and increases the potential for rear-end crashes at 13th Avenue.
As such, ATEC recommends Alternative 2A. In addition, ATEC recommends the following
improvements at the intersection of Hollywood Blvd and 13th Avenue:
Schedule maintenance for the video detection at the intersection.
Provide back-plates at the signal heads to improve visibility during the AM and PM
periods. It should be noted that this would require a structural analysis of the existing
infrastructure. If the analysis determines that the implementation of back-plates would
require replacing the mast arms, this recommendation can be addressed at a later time.

The objective of this study is to analyze the operational capacity of the City of
Hollywood’s alternative design proposals for the corridor of SR 820/Hollywood
Boulevard from approximately the east side of Young Circle to the Intracoastal
Waterway Bridge. Three (3) different geometric configurations involving roundabouts
were analyzed and compared to the roadway’s existing conditions, which essentially
consists of two-way directional median openings at all odd-numbered side streets, no
median openings at all even-numbered side streets (right-in/right-out only) and traffic
provide more detailed information as to the comparative analyses performed and
includes our final recommendation, based upon the output of the respective Synchro 8
models that were developed, travel time studies, City input, and engineering judgment.
The analysis was conducted by obtaining 72-hour approach volume counts, peak hour
Turning Movement Counts (TMC’s), Travel Time and Delay studies, existing
geometrics, pedestrian and bicycle volumes, distance to other intersections, crash data
for the last three years, and posted speed limits along Hollywood Boulevard within the
study limits. The data and roadway geometric characteristics were used to create an
Different design alternatives were subsequently created for the purpose of obtaining
Level of Service (LOS) and delay data for each modeled configuration from the micro-
simulation output, which were then compared to determine the most favorable option.
The resulting measures of effectiveness were then compared to the Synchro output
from the existing conditions model to determine whether any significant adverse
operational or safety conditions would result from either of the proposed alternatives.

In order to better understand the needs of the project (specifically at the intersection of
Avenue and Hollywood Blvd), the hard copy police reports were reviewed at the
intersection for the years 2011, 2012, 2013 and 2014. These were compared to the
most recent crash data available from the FDOT’s Crash Analysis Reporting System
(CARS). An Expected Value Analysis worksheet was developed by the Department’s
District 6 Traffic Operations office in order to compare a given intersection’s crash
frequency with other locations throughout their jurisdiction with similar geometric
characteristics. It is recognized that this tool is not used in District 4; however, it does
provide a reasonable comparison of like facilities in South Florida. A summary of the

angle collisions. Two crashes occurred due to the driver failing to yield to the red light.

that were abnormally high for the 90th and 95th percentiles, respectively. These include
collision with a parked car (4), collision with a fixed object (4), and overturned (2), for the
three years of the review. Based upon numerous field observations and input from City
staff, it is most likely that the primary cause of these crashes can be attributed to
motorists travelling well above the posted 40 MPH speed limit. As a cautionary
measure, the intersection’s signal timing plan was reviewed and it was determined that
the Yellow and All-Red timing values are in compliance with prevailing guidelines. In
addition, the Expected Value Analysis also shows a high 90th and 95th percentile
The 2014 crash data (not shown in the analysis) reveals that there have been two
collisions involving westbound left turning vehicles to date. Therefore, it is
recommended that this intersection’s crash frequency continue to be monitored in order
to determine whether protected left turn phasing is warranted in the future.

page.text: Similar to Existing Conditions, Alternative 1 shows minimal delay along the east and
westbound directions, while maintaining a delay of approximately 10 seconds along the
north and southbound directions. Alternatives 2A and 2B maintain this same level of
delay for north and southbound approaches; however, the delay for east and westbound
directions was shown to increase for both AM and PM periods, respectively. The
intersection Level of Service (LOS) changed from LOS A to LOS B under Alternatives
2A and 2B, maintaining an acceptable LOS and delay.

page.text: The Existing Conditions show minimal delay along the east and westbound directions
with about a 10-second delay along the NB/SB direction. Alternatives 1, 2A and 2B
show an increase in delay for all approaches. However, it is worth noting that Alternative
1 allows for NB/SB traffic, while Alternatives 2A and 2B only allow for NB/SB Rights. As
such, Alternative 1 compromises operations by allowing for more accessibility. The
intersection remained at LOS A under Alternatives 2A and 2B.
The Existing Conditions show the signalized intersection with a LOS B at each
approach, except for LOS C at the NB approach. All of the Alternatives show an
improvement along the NB approach, with a LOS of B. However, Alternative 1, which
features a roundabout, shows LOS C for the SB movement, with delay reaching 23.6
seconds per vehicle. This is due to the high volume entering the intersection from the
north side (Polk Street). The intersection remained at LOS B for Alternatives 2A and 2B.
The Existing Conditions show minimal delay along the EB/WB approaches, with a delay
of 10-11 seconds along the NB/SB approaches. Alternative 1, which aims to maintain
these conditions, shows similar LOS and Delay as the Existing Condition. Alternatives
2A and 2B, however, show a decrease in delay along the NB/SB conditions (about 7
seconds compared to 10), but exhibits an increase in delay along the EB/WB
movements (from LOS A to B/C). The intersection LOS changed from LOS A to LOS
A/B under Alternatives 2A and 2B, maintaining an acceptable LOS and delay.
It should be noted that the delay and LOS increase is not only related to the
implementation of a roundabout, but also due to the capacity reduction associated with
the proposed two-to-one travel lane reduction along east and westbound Hollywood
Boulevard in advance of the proposed roundabouts. In addition, roundabouts are
typically suited better for intersections with relatively low volumes. Signalized
intersections not only can better accommodate high traffic volumes, but the signal
timing can also be modified to better adapt to traffic patterns.
